<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-473-292  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 473 292.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  July 31 1989 v10 n30 p14(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>How to avoid LAN mines. (avoiding problems in local area networkadministration)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dern, Daniel P.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>There are a number of basic steps that can be taken by thesmall-to-medium business user of microcomputer-based local areanetworks (LAN) to ensure efficient operation and minimize thepossibility of LAN disasters.andP;  Training and solid backup planningwill eliminate most routine disasters such as accidental file ordatabase deletion.andP;  The careful planning and execution of cablingand installation is the foundation of any successful LAN.andP;  With anestimated 1.5 million LANs installed as of early 1989, there is noshortage of trained system administrators to oversee operations.andO;A knowledgeable in-house person who is responsible for the overallnetwork management is preferable to less cost-effective outsidecontractors.andP;  LAN products must be selected that are in concertwith plans for network growth.andP;  Finally, users must be consultedbefore a LAN strategy is implemented.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Local Area NetworksPlanningNetwork ManagementDisaster PlanningUser Relations.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   LAN Do's and Don'ts. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>